# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mrna-vaccines
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] In molecular biology, the **five-prime cap** (**5′ cap**) is a specially altered nucleotide on the 5′ end of some primary transcripts such as precursor messenger RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] This process, known as **mRNA capping**, is highly regulated and vital in the creation of stable and mature messenger RNA able to undergo translation during protein synthesis.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Mitochondrial mRNA and chloroplastic mRNA are not capped.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] In eukaryotes, the 5′ cap (cap-0), found on the 5′ end of an mRNA molecule, consists of a guanine nucleotide connected to mRNA via an unusual 5′ to 5′ triphosphate linkage.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] This guanosine is methylated on the 7 position directly after capping *in vivo* by a methyltransferase.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] It is referred to as a 7-methylguanylate cap, abbreviated m7G.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] The Cap-0 is the base cap structure, however, the first and second transcribed nucleotides can also be 2' O-methylated, leading to the Cap-1 and Cap-2 structures, respectively.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] This is more common in higher eukaryotes and thought to be part of the innate immune system to recognize mRNAs from other organisms.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] The 5′ cap is chemically similar to the 3′ end of an RNA molecule (the 5′ carbon of the cap ribose is bonded, and the 3′ unbonded).
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] This provides significant resistance to 5′ exonucleases.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Small nuclear RNAs contain unique 5′-caps.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Sm-class snRNAs are found with 5′-trimethylguanosine caps, while Lsm-class snRNAs are found with 5′-monomethylphosphate caps.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] In bacteria, and potentially also in higher organisms, some RNAs are capped with NAD+, NADH, or 3′-dephospho-coenzyme A.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] In all organisms, mRNA molecules can be decapped in a process known as messenger RNA decapping.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] This is usually followed by degradation of the mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] The starting point for capping with 7-methylguanylate is the unaltered 5′ end of an RNA molecule, which terminates at a triphosphate group.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] This features a final nucleotide followed by three phosphate groups attached to the 5′ carbon.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] The capping process is initiated before the completion of transcription, as the nascent pre-mRNA is being synthesized.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] GTP is added to the terminal bisphosphate by mRNA guanylyltransferase, losing a pyrophosphate from the GTP substrate in the process.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] If the nearest cap-adjacent nucleotide is 2′-*O*-ribose methyl-adenosine (i.e.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] 5′(m7Gp)(ppAm)[pN]n), it can be further methylated at the N6 methyl position to form *N*6-methyladenosine, resulting in 5′(m7Gp)(ppm6Am)[pN]n.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] The mechanism of capping with NAD+, NADH, or 3′-dephospho-coenzyme A is different.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Both bacterial RNA polymerase and eukaryotic RNA polymerase II are able to carry out this "ab initio capping mechanism".
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] For capping with 7-methylguanylate, the capping enzyme complex (CEC) binds to RNA polymerase II before transcription starts.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] As soon as the 5′ end of the new transcript emerges from RNA polymerase II, the CEC carries out the capping process (this kind of mechanism ensures capping, as with polyadenylation).
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] The enzymes for capping can only bind to RNA polymerase II, ensuring specificity to only these transcripts, which are almost entirely mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Capping with NAD+, NADH, or 3′-dephospho-coenzyme A is targeted by promoter sequence.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Capping with NAD+, NADH, or 3′-dephospho-coenzyme A occurs only at promoters that have certain sequences at and immediately upstream of the transcription start site and therefore occurs only for RNAs synthesized from certain promoters.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Promotion of 5′ proximal intron excision.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Nuclear export of RNA is regulated by the cap binding complex (CBC), which binds exclusively to 7-methylguanylate-capped RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] The CBC is then recognized by the nuclear pore complex and exported.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Once in the cytoplasm after the pioneer round of translation, the CBC is replaced by the translation factors eIF4E and eIF4G of the eIF4F complex.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] This complex is then recognized by other translation initiation machinery including the ribosome.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Capping with 7-methylguanylate prevents 5′ degradation in two ways.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] First, degradation of the mRNA by 5′ exonucleases is prevented (as mentioned above) by functionally looking like a 3′ end.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Second, the CBC and eIF4E/eIF4G block the access of decapping enzymes to the cap.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] This increases the half-life of the mRNA, essential in eukaryotes as the export and translation processes take significant time.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Decapping of a 7-methylguanylate-capped mRNA is catalyzed by the decapping complex made up of at least Dcp1 and Dcp2, which must compete with eIF4E to bind the cap.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Thus the 7-methylguanylate cap is a marker of an actively translating mRNA and is used by cells to regulate mRNA half-lives in response to new stimuli.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] Undesirable mRNAs are sent to P-bodies for temporary storage or decapping, the details of which are still being resolved.
[src:mrna-vaccines/five-prime-cap] The mechanism of 5′ proximal intron excision promotion is not well understood, but the 7-methylguanylate cap appears to loop around and interact with the spliceosome in the splicing process, promoting intron excision.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Sometimes the term "LNP" describes all lipid-based nanoparticles.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] In specific applications, LNPs describe a specific type of lipid-based nanoparticle, such as the LNPs used for the mRNA vaccine.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Using LNPs for drug delivery was first approved in 2018 for the siRNA drug Onpattro.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] LNPs became more widely known late in 2020, as some COVID-19 vaccines that use RNA vaccine technology coat the fragile mRNA strands with PEGylated lipid nanoparticles as their delivery vehicle (including both the Moderna and the Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccines).
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] A lipid nanoparticle is typically spherical with an average diameter between 10 and 1000 nanometers.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] LNPs are made up of phospholipids, cholesterols, ionizable lipids, and polyethylene glycol-derived lipids (PEGylated lipids).
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Each of these components play a key role in LNPs used for mRNA vaccines that target SARS-CoV-2 (the virus that causes COVID-19).
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] The ionizable cationic lipids bind to mRNA, PEGylated lipids stabilize LNPs, and phospholipids and cholesterol give LNPs their structure.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Because of rapid clearance by the immune system of the positively charged lipid, neutral ionizable amino lipids were developed.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] A novel squaramide lipid (a partially aromatic four-membered ring that can participate in pi–pi interactions) has been used as part of the delivery system used, for example, by Moderna.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Solid lipid nanoparticles (SLNs) possess a solid lipid core matrix that solubilizes lipophilic molecules.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Surfactants (emulsifiers) stabilize the lipid core.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] The emulsifier used depends on administration routes, and is more limited for parenteral administrations.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] The term "lipid" refers to a broader class of molecules, and includes triglycerides (e.g. tristearin), diglycerides (e.g. glycerol bahenate), monoglycerides (e.g. glycerol monostearate), fatty acids (e.g. stearic acid), steroids (e.g. cholesterol), and waxes (e.g. cetyl palmitate).
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] All classes of emulsifiers (with respect to charge and molecular weight) have been used to stabilize the lipid dispersion.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] It has been found that the combination of emulsifiers might prevent particle agglomeration more efficiently.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] An SLN is generally spherical and consists of a solid lipid core stabilized by a surfactant.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] The core lipids can be fatty acids, acylglycerols, waxes, and mixtures of these surfactants.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Biological membrane lipids, such as phospholipids, sphingomyelins, bile salts (sodium taurocholate), and sterols (cholesterol) are used as stabilizers.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Biological lipids having minimum carrier cytotoxicity and the solid state of the lipid permit better controlled drug release due to increased mass transfer resistance.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Nanostructured lipid carriers (NLCs) are lipid-based nanoparticles that contain a mixture of solid and liquid lipids in the central core of the lipid carrier.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] NLCs are derived from SLNs by injecting liquid lipids into the solid core, resulting in a non-uniform internal core.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] This modification allows for higher drug capacity and more controlled drug delivery.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Lipid-based nanoparticles are generally prepared by formulation and self-assembly processes rather than by chemical synthesis of the final particle.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Common preparation methods include homogenisation, ultrasonication, solvent emulsification and evaporation, microemulsion-based methods, ethanol injection, and controlled mixing of lipid-containing organic phases with aqueous phases.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] In these methods, formulation composition, solvent conditions, lipid concentration, flow-rate ratio, total flow rate, temperature and downstream processing can strongly affect the final nanoparticle population.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Development of solid lipid nanoparticles is one of the emerging fields of lipid nanotechnology (for a review on lipid nanotechnology, see ) with several potential applications in drug delivery, clinical medicine and research, as well as in other disciplines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Due to their unique size-dependent properties, lipid nanoparticles can possibly develop new therapeutics.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] The ability to incorporate drugs into nanocarriers offers a new prototype in drug delivery that could hold great promise for attaining bioavailability enhancement along with controlled and site-specific drug delivery.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] SLNs are also considered to be well tolerated in general, due to their composition from physiologically similar lipids.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] The conventional approaches such as use of permeation enhancers, surface modification, prodrug synthesis, complex formation and colloidal lipid carrier-based strategies have been developed for the delivery of drugs to intestinal lymphatics.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] In addition, polymeric nanoparticles, self-emulsifying delivery systems, liposomes, microemulsions, micellar solutions and recently, solid lipid nanoparticles (SLN) have been exploited as probable possibilities as carriers for oral intestinal lymphatic delivery.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Solid lipid nanoparticles can function as the basis for oral and parenteral drug delivery systems.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] SLNs combine the advantages of lipid emulsion and polymeric nanoparticle systems while overcoming the temporal and *in vivo* stability issues that troubles the conventional as well as polymeric nanoparticles drug delivery approaches.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Various functions such as molecules for targeting, PEG chains for stealth properties, or thiol groups for adhesion via disulfide bond formation can be immobilized on their surface.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] A recent study has demonstrated the use of solid lipid nanoparticles as a platform for oral delivery of the nutrient mineral iron, by incorporating the hydrophilic molecule ferrous sulfate (FeSO4) in a lipid matrix composed of stearic acid.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Carvedilol-loaded solid lipid nanoparticles were prepared using hot-homogenization technique for oral delivery with compritol and poloxamer 188 as the lipid and surfactant, respectively.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Another example of drug delivery using SLN would be oral solid SLN suspended in distilled water, which was synthesized to trap drugs within the SLN structure.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Upon ingestion, the SLNs are exposed to gastric and intestinal acids that dissolve the SLNs and release the drugs into the system.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Many nano-structured systems have been employed for ocular drug delivery.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] SLNs have been looked at as a potential drug carrier system since the 1990s.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] SLNs do not show biotoxicity as they are prepared from physiological lipids.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] SLNs are useful in ocular drug delivery as they can enhance the corneal absorption of drugs and improve the ocular bioavailability of both hydrophilic and lipophilic drugs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] SLNs have another advantage of allowing autoclave sterilization, a necessary step towards formulation of ocular preparations.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Advantages of SLNs include the use of physiological lipids (which decreases the danger of acute and chronic toxicity), the avoidance of organic solvents, a potential wide application spectrum (dermal, per os, intravenous) and the high pressure homogenization as an established production method.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Additionally, improved bioavailability, protection of sensitive drug molecules from the outer environment (e.g. water, light), and even controlled release characteristics were claimed by the incorporation of poorly water-soluble drugs in the solid lipid matrix.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Moreover, SLNs can carry both lipophilic and hydrophilic drugs, and are more affordable compared to polymeric/surfactant-based carriers.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] A significant obstacle to using LNPs as a delivery vehicle for nucleic acids is that in nature, lipids and nucleic acids both carry a negative electric charge—meaning they do not easily mix with each other.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] While working at Syntex in the mid-1980s, Philip Felgner pioneered the use of artificially-created cationic lipids (positively-charged lipids) to bind lipids to nucleic acids in order to transfect the latter into cells.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] However, by the late 1990s, it was known from *in vitro* experiments that this use of cationic lipids had undesired side effects on cell membranes.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] As of 2021, the current understanding of LNPs formulated with such ionizable cationic lipids is that they enter cells through receptor-mediated endocytosis and end up inside endosomes.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] The acidity inside the endosomes causes LNPs' ionizable cationic lipids to acquire a positive charge, and this is thought to allow LNPs to escape from endosomes and release their RNA payloads.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] From 2005 into the early 2010s, LNPs were investigated as a drug delivery system for small interfering RNA (siRNA) drugs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] In 2009, Cullis co-founded a company called Acuitas Therapeutics to commercialize his LNP research; Acuitas worked on developing LNPs for Alnylam Pharmaceuticals's siRNA drugs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] In 2018, the FDA approved Alnylam's siRNA drug Onpattro (patisiran), the first drug to use LNPs as the drug delivery system.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] By that point in time, siRNA drug developers like Alnylam were already looking at other options for future drugs like chemical conjugate systems, but during the 2010s, the earlier research into using LNPs for siRNA became a foundation for new research into using LNPs for mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Lipids intended for short siRNA strands did not work well for much longer mRNA strands, which led to extensive research during the mid-2010s into the creation of novel ionizable cationic lipids appropriate for mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] As of late 2020, several mRNA vaccines for SARS-CoV-2 use LNPs as their drug delivery system, including both the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine and the Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Moderna uses its own proprietary ionizable cationic lipid called SM-102, while Pfizer and BioNTech licensed an ionizable cationic lipid called ALC-0315 from Acuitas.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Elucidation of intestinal lymphatic absorption mechanism from solid lipid nanoparticles using Caco-2 cell line as in vitro model was developed.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] Several researchers have shown the enhancement of oral bioavailibility of poorly water-soluble drugs when encapsulated in solid lipid nanoparticle.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] This enhanced bioavailibility is achieved via lymphatic delivery.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] To elucidate the absorption mechanism, from solid lipid nanoparticle, human excised Caco-2 cell monolayer could be alternative tissue for development of an in-vitro model to be used as a screening tool before animal studies are undertaken.
[src:mrna-vaccines/lipid-nanoparticle] The results obtained in this model suggested that the main absorption mechanism of carvedilol loaded solid lipid nanoparticle could be endocytosis and, more specifically, clathrin-mediated endocytosis.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] An **mRNA** **vaccine** is a type of vaccine that uses a copy of a molecule called messenger RNA (mRNA) to produce an immune response.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The vaccine delivers molecules of antigen-encoding mRNA into cells, which use the designed mRNA as a blueprint to build foreign protein that would normally be produced by a pathogen (such as a virus) or by a cancer cell.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] These protein molecules stimulate an adaptive immune response that teaches the body to identify and destroy the corresponding pathogen or cancer cells.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The mRNA is delivered by a co-formulation of the RNA encapsulated in lipid nanoparticles that protect the RNA strands and help their absorption into the cells.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Reactogenicity, the tendency of a vaccine to produce adverse reactions, is similar to that of conventional non-RNA vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] People susceptible to an autoimmune response may have an adverse reaction to messenger RNA vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The advantages of mRNA vaccines over traditional vaccines are ease of design, speed and lower cost of production, the induction of both cellular and humoral immunity, and lack of interaction with the genomic DNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] While some messenger RNA vaccines, such as the Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine, have the disadvantage of requiring ultracold storage before distribution, other mRNA vaccines, such as the Moderna vaccine, do not have such requirements.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In RNA therapeutics, messenger RNA vaccines have attracted considerable interest as COVID-19 vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In December 2020, Pfizer–BioNTech and Moderna obtained authorization for their mRNA-based COVID-19 vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] On 2 December, the UK Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) became the first medicines regulator to approve an mRNA vaccine, authorizing the Pfizer–BioNTech vaccine for widespread use.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] On 11 December, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) issued an emergency use authorization for the Pfizer–BioNTech vaccine and a week later similarly authorized the Moderna vaccine.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In 2023 the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine was awarded to Katalin Karikó and Drew Weissman for their discoveries concerning modified nucleosides that enabled the development of effective mRNA vaccines against COVID-19.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The first successful transfection of designed mRNA packaged within a liposomal nanoparticle into a cell was published in 1989.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] "Naked" (or unprotected) lab-made mRNA was injected a year later into the muscle of mice.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] These studies were the first evidence that *in vitro* transcribed mRNA with a chosen gene was able to deliver the genetic information to produce a desired protein within living cell tissue and led to the concept proposal of messenger RNA vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Liposome-encapsulated mRNA encoding a viral antigen was shown in 1993 to stimulate T cells in mice.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The following year self-amplifying mRNA was developed by including both a viral antigen and replicase encoding gene.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The method was used in mice to elicit both a humoral and cellular immune response against a viral pathogen.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The next year mRNA encoding a tumor antigen was shown to elicit a similar immune response against cancer cells in mice.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The first human clinical trial using *ex vivo* dendritic cells transfected with mRNA encoding tumor antigens (therapeutic cancer mRNA vaccine) was started in 2001.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Four years later, the successful use of modified nucleosides as a method to transport mRNA inside cells without setting off the body's defense system was reported.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Clinical trial results of an mRNA vaccine directly injected into the body against cancer cells were reported in 2008.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] BioNTech in 2008, and Moderna in 2010, were founded to develop mRNA biotechnologies.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The US research agency DARPA launched at this time the biotechnology research program ADEPT to develop emerging technologies for the US military.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The agency recognized the potential of nucleic acid technology for defense against pandemics and began to invest in the field.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] DARPA grants were seen as a vote of confidence that in turn encouraged other government agencies and private investors to invest in mRNA technology.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] DARPA awarded at the time a $25 million grant to Moderna.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The first human clinical trials using an mRNA vaccine against an infectious agent (rabies) began in 2013.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Over the next few years, clinical trials of mRNA vaccines for a number of other viruses were started. mRNA vaccines for human use were studied for infectious agents such as influenza, Zika virus, cytomegalovirus, and Chikungunya virus.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The COVID-19 pandemic, and sequencing of the causative virus SARS-CoV-2 at the beginning of 2020, led to the rapid development of the first approved mRNA vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] BioNTech and Moderna in December of the same year obtained approval for their mRNA-based COVID-19 vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In December 2020, the UK Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) became the first global medicines regulator in history to approve an mRNA vaccine, granting emergency authorization for Pfizer–BioNTech's BNT162b2 COVID-19 vaccine for widespread use.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Also, in December 2020, the US Food and Drug Administration gave emergency use authorization for the Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine and the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] A combined messenger RNA vaccine for protection against influenza and COVID‑19 was introduced in 2026.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The goal of a vaccine is to stimulate the adaptive immune system to create antibodies that precisely target that particular pathogen.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The markers on the pathogen that the antibodies target are called antigens.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Traditional vaccines stimulate an antibody response by injecting either antigens, an attenuated (weakened) virus, an inactivated (dead) virus, or a recombinant antigen-encoding viral vector (harmless carrier virus with an antigen transgene) into the body.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] These antigens and viruses are prepared and grown outside the body.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In contrast, mRNA vaccines introduce a short-lived synthetically created fragment of the RNA sequence of a virus into the individual being vaccinated.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] These mRNA fragments are taken up by dendritic cells through phagocytosis.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The dendritic cells use their internal machinery (ribosomes) to read the mRNA and produce the viral antigens that the mRNA encodes.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The body degrades the mRNA fragments within a few days of introduction.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Although non-immune cells can potentially also absorb vaccine mRNA, produce antigens, and display the antigens on their surfaces, dendritic cells absorb the mRNA globules much more readily.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The mRNA fragments are translated in the cytoplasm and do not affect the body's genomic DNA, located separately in the cell nucleus.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Once the viral antigens are produced by the host cell, the normal adaptive immune system processes are followed.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Antigens are broken down by proteasomes.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Class I and class II MHC molecules then attach to the antigen and transport it to the cellular membrane, "activating" the dendritic cell.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Once activated, dendritic cells migrate to lymph nodes, where they present the antigen to T cells and B cells.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] This triggers the production of antibodies specifically targeted to the antigen, ultimately resulting in immunity.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The central component of a mRNA vaccine is its mRNA construct.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The *in vitro* transcribed mRNA is generated from an engineered plasmid DNA, which has an RNA polymerase promoter and sequence which corresponds to the mRNA construct.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] By combining T7 phage RNA polymerase and the plasmid DNA, the mRNA can be transcribed in the lab.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Efficacy of the vaccine is dependent on the stability and structure of the designed mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The *in vitro* transcribed mRNA has the same structural components as natural mRNA in eukaryotic cells.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] It has a 5' cap, a 5'-untranslated region (UTR) and 3'-UTR, an open reading frame (ORF), which encodes the relevant antigen, and a 3'-poly(A) tail.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] By modifying these different components of the synthetic mRNA, the stability and translational ability of the mRNA can be enhanced, and in turn, the efficacy of the vaccine improved.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The mRNA can be improved by using synthetic 5'-cap analogues which enhance the stability and increase protein translation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Similarly, regulatory elements in the 5'-untranslated region and the 3'-untranslated region can be altered, and the length of the poly(A) tail optimized, to stabilize the mRNA and increase protein production.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The mRNA nucleotides can be modified to both decrease innate immune activation and increase the mRNA's half-life in the host cell.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The nucleic acid sequence and codon usage impacts protein translation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Enriching the sequence with guanine-cytosine content improves mRNA stability and half-life and, in turn, protein production.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Replacing rare codons with synonymous codons frequently used by the host cell also enhances protein production.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] For a vaccine to be successful, sufficient mRNA must enter the host cell cytoplasm to stimulate production of the specific antigens.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Entry of mRNA molecules, however, faces a number of difficulties.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Not only are mRNA molecules too large to cross the cell membrane by simple diffusion, they are also negatively charged like the cell membrane, which causes a mutual electrostatic repulsion.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Additionally, mRNA is easily degraded by RNAases in skin and blood.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Various methods have been developed to overcome these delivery hurdles.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The method of vaccine delivery can be broadly classified by whether mRNA transfer into cells occurs within (*in vivo*) or outside (*ex vivo*) the organism.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Dendritic cells display antigens on their surfaces, leading to interactions with T cells to initiate an immune response.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Dendritic cells can be collected from patients and programmed with the desired mRNA, then administered back into patients to create an immune response.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The simplest way that *ex vivo* dendritic cells take up mRNA molecules is through endocytosis, a fairly inefficient pathway in the laboratory setting that can be significantly improved through electroporation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Since the discovery that the direct administration of *in vitro* transcribed mRNA leads to the expression of antigens in the body, *in vivo* approaches have been investigated.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] They offer some advantages over *ex vivo* methods, particularly by avoiding the cost of harvesting and adapting dendritic cells from patients and by imitating a regular infection.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Different routes of injection, such as into the skin, blood, or muscles, result in varying levels of mRNA uptake, making the choice of administration route a critical aspect of *in vivo* delivery.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] One study showed, in comparing different routes, that lymph node injection leads to the largest T-cell response.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Naked mRNA injection means that the delivery of the vaccine is only done in a buffer solution.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] This mode of mRNA uptake has been known since the 1990s.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The first worldwide clinical studies used intradermal injections of naked mRNA for vaccination.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] A variety of methods have been used to deliver naked mRNA, such as subcutaneous, intravenous, and intratumoral injections.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Although naked mRNA delivery causes an immune response, the effect is relatively weak, and after injection the mRNA is often rapidly degraded.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Cationic polymers can be mixed with mRNA to generate protective coatings called polyplexes.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] These protect the recombinant mRNA from ribonucleases and assist its penetration in cells.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Protamine is a natural cationic peptide and has been used to encapsulate mRNA for vaccination.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The first time the FDA approved the use of lipid nanoparticles as a drug delivery system was in 2018, when the agency approved the first siRNA drug, Onpattro.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Encapsulating the mRNA molecule in lipid nanoparticles was a critical breakthrough for producing viable mRNA vaccines, solving a number of key technical barriers in delivering the mRNA molecule into the host cell.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Research into using lipids to deliver siRNA to cells became a foundation for similar research into using lipids to deliver mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] However, new lipids had to be invented to encapsulate mRNA strands, which are much longer than siRNA strands.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Principally, the lipid provides a layer of protection against degradation, allowing more robust translational output.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In addition, the customization of the lipid's outer layer allows the targeting of desired cell types through ligand interactions.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] However, many studies have also highlighted the difficulty of studying this type of delivery, demonstrating that there is an inconsistency between *in vivo* and *in vitro* applications of nanoparticles in terms of cellular intake.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The nanoparticles can be administered to the body and transported via multiple routes, such as intravenously or through the lymphatic system.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] One issue with lipid nanoparticles is that several of the breakthroughs leading to the practical use of that technology involve the use of microfluidics.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Microfluidic reaction chambers are difficult to scale up, since the entire point of microfluidics is to exploit the microscale behaviors of liquids.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The only way around this obstacle is to run an extensive number of microfluidic reaction chambers in parallel, a novel task requiring custom-built equipment.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] For COVID-19 mRNA vaccines, this was the main manufacturing bottleneck.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Pfizer used such a parallel approach to solve the scaling problem.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Another issue, with the large-scale use of this delivery method, is the availability of the novel lipids used to create lipid nanoparticles, especially ionizable cationic lipids.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Before 2020, such lipids were manufactured in small quantities measured in grams or kilograms, and they were used for medical research and a handful of drugs for rare conditions.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] As the safety and efficacy of mRNA vaccines became clear in 2020, the few companies able to manufacture the requisite lipids were confronted with the challenge of scaling up production to respond to orders for several tons of lipids.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In addition to non-viral delivery methods, RNA viruses have been engineered to achieve similar immunological responses.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Typical RNA viruses used as vectors include retroviruses, lentiviruses, alphaviruses and rhabdoviruses, each of which can differ in structure and function.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Clinical studies have utilized such viruses on a range of diseases in model animals such as mice, chicken and primates.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] mRNA vaccines offer specific advantages over traditional vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Because mRNA vaccines are not constructed from an active pathogen (or even an inactivated pathogen), they are non-infectious.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In contrast, traditional vaccines require the production of pathogens, which, if done at high volumes, could increase the risks of localized outbreaks of the virus at the production facility.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Another biological advantage of mRNA vaccines is that since the antigens are produced inside the cell, they stimulate cellular immunity, as well as humoral immunity.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] mRNA vaccines have the production advantage that they can be designed swiftly.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Moderna designed their mRNA-1273 vaccine for COVID-19 in 2 days.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] They can also be manufactured faster, more cheaply, and in a more standardized fashion (with fewer error rates in production), which can improve responsiveness to serious outbreaks.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The Pfizer–BioNTech vaccine originally required 110 days to mass-produce (before Pfizer began to optimize the manufacturing process to only 60 days), which was substantially faster than traditional flu and polio vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The majority of the days needed for each production run are allocated to rigorous quality control at each stage.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In addition to sharing the advantages of theoretical DNA vaccines over established traditional vaccines, mRNA vaccines also have additional advantages over DNA vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The mRNA is translated in the cytosol, so there is no need for the RNA to enter the cell nucleus, and the risk of being integrated into the host genome is averted.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Modified nucleosides (for example, pseudouridines, 2'-O-methylated nucleosides) can be incorporated to mRNA to suppress immune response stimulation to avoid immediate degradation and produce a more persistent effect through enhanced translation capacity.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The open reading frame (ORF) and untranslated regions (UTR) of mRNA can be optimized for different purposes (a process called sequence engineering of mRNA), for example through enriching the guanine-cytosine content or choosing specific UTRs known to increase translation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] An additional ORF coding for a replication mechanism can be added to amplify antigen translation and therefore immune response, decreasing the amount of starting material needed.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Because mRNA is fragile, some vaccines must be kept at very low temperatures to avoid degrading and thus giving little effective immunity to the recipient.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Pfizer–BioNTech's BNT162b2 mRNA vaccine has to be kept between −80 and −60 °C (−112 and −76 °F).
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Moderna says their mRNA-1273 vaccine can be stored between −25 and −15 °C (−13 and 5 °F), which is comparable to a home freezer, and that it remains stable between 2 and 8 °C (36 and 46 °F) for up to 30 days.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Before 2020, no mRNA technology platform (drug or vaccine) had been approved for therapeutic use in humans, so there was a risk of unknown effects.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Reactogenicity is similar to that of conventional, non-RNA vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] However, those susceptible to an autoimmune response may have an adverse reaction to mRNA vaccines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The mRNA strands in the vaccine may elicit an unintended immune reaction – this entails the body believing itself to be sick, and the person feeling as if they are as a result.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] To minimize this, mRNA sequences in mRNA vaccines are designed to mimic those produced by host cells.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Strong but transient reactogenic effects were reported in trials of novel COVID-19 mRNA vaccines; most people will not experience severe side effects which include fever and fatigue.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Severe side effects are defined as those that prevent daily activity.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The COVID-19 mRNA vaccines from Moderna and Pfizer–BioNTech had short-term efficacy rates of over 90 percent against the original SARS-CoV-2 virus.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Prior to mRNA, drug trials on pathogens other than COVID-19 were not effective and had to be abandoned in the early phases of trials.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The reason for the efficacy of the new mRNA vaccines is not clear.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] These reactions though severe were transient and another view is that they were believed to be a reaction to the lipid drug delivery molecules.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] In June 2021, the US FDA added a warning about the possibility of increased risk of myocarditis and pericarditis for some people.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] There is misinformation implying that mRNA vaccines could alter DNA in the nucleus. mRNA in the cytosol is rapidly degraded, before it would have time to gain entry into the cell nucleus.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Retrovirus can be single-stranded RNA (just as many SARS-CoV-2 vaccines are single-stranded RNA) which enters the cell nucleus and uses reverse transcriptase to make DNA from the RNA in the cell nucleus.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] A retrovirus has mechanisms to be imported into the nucleus, but other mRNA (such as the vaccine) lack these mechanisms.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Once inside the nucleus, creation of DNA from RNA cannot occur without a reverse transcriptase and appropriate primers, which both accompany a retrovirus, but which would not be present for other exogenous mRNA (such as a vaccine) even if it could enter the nucleus.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] mRNA vaccines use either non-amplifying (conventional) mRNA or self-amplifying mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Pfizer–BioNTech and Moderna vaccines use non-amplifying mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Both mRNA types continue to be investigated as vaccine methods against other potential pathogens and cancer.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The initial mRNA vaccines use a non-amplifying mRNA construct.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Non-amplifying mRNA has only one open reading frame that codes for the antigen of interest.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The total amount of mRNA available to the cell is equal to the amount delivered by the vaccine.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Dosage strength is limited by the amount of mRNA that can be delivered by the vaccine.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Non-amplifying vaccines replace uridine with N1-Methylpseudouridine in an attempt to reduce toxicity.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Self-amplifying mRNA (saRNA) vaccines replicate their mRNA after transfection.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Self-amplifying mRNA has two open reading frames.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The first frame, like conventional mRNA, codes for the antigen of interest.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The second frame codes for an RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (and its helper proteins) which replicates the mRNA construct in the cell.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The mechanisms and consequently the evaluation of self-amplifying mRNA may be different, as self-amplifying mRNA is a much bigger molecule.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] SaRNA vaccines being researched include a malaria vaccine.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The first saRNA Covid vaccine authorised was Gemcovac, in India in June 2022.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The second was ARCT-154, developed by Arcturus Therapeutics.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] A version manufactured by Meiji Seika Pharma was authorised in Japan in November 2023.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] GSK began a phase 1 trial of an saRNA COVID-19 vaccine in 2021.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] Gritstone bio started also started a phase 1 trial of an saRNA COVID-19 vaccine in 2021, used as a booster vaccine, with interim results published in 2023.
[src:mrna-vaccines/mrna-vaccine] The vaccine is designed to target both the spike protein of the SARS‑CoV‑2 virus, and viral proteins that may be less prone to genetic variation, to provide greater protection against SARS‑CoV‑2 variants. saRNA vaccines must use uridine, which is required for reproduction to occur.
[src:mrna-vaccines/nucleoside] The line-angle molecular representation implies carbon atoms at each angle, each with enough hydrogen atoms to fill its four-bond valency.
[src:mrna-vaccines/nucleoside] Each chemical has a short symbol, useful when the chemical family is clear from the context, and a longer symbol, if further disambiguation is needed.
[src:mrna-vaccines/nucleoside] For example, long nucleobase sequences in genomes are usually described by CATG symbols, not Cyt-Ade-Thy-Gua (see *Nucleic acid sequence § Notation*).
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The process of polyadenylation begins as the transcription of a gene terminates.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The 3′-most segment of the newly made pre-mRNA is first cleaved off by a set of proteins; these proteins then synthesize the poly(A) tail at the RNA's 3′ end.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In some genes these proteins add a poly(A) tail at one of several possible sites.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Therefore, polyadenylation can produce more than one transcript from a single gene (**alternative polyadenylation**), similar to alternative splicing.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The poly(A) tail is important for the nuclear export, translation and stability of mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The tail is shortened over time, and, when it is short enough, the mRNA is enzymatically degraded.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] However, in a few cell types, mRNAs with short poly(A) tails are stored for later activation by re-polyadenylation in the cytosol.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In contrast, when polyadenylation occurs in bacteria, it promotes RNA degradation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This is also sometimes the case for eukaryotic non-coding RNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] mRNA molecules in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes have polyadenylated 3′-ends, with the prokaryotic poly(A) tails generally shorter and fewer mRNA molecules polyadenylated.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] RNAs are a type of large biological molecules, whose individual building blocks are called nucleotides.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The name *poly(A) tail* (for polyadenylic acid tail) reflects the way RNA nucleotides are abbreviated, with a letter for the base the nucleotide contains (A for adenine, C for cytosine, G for guanine and U for uracil).
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] RNAs are produced (*transcribed*) from a DNA template.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] By convention, RNA sequences are written in a 5′ to 3′ direction.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The 5′ end is the part of the RNA molecule that is transcribed first, and the 3′ end is transcribed last.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The 3′ end is also where the poly(A) tail is found on polyadenylated RNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Messenger RNA (mRNA) is RNA that has a coding region that acts as a template for protein synthesis (*translation*).
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The rest of the mRNA, the *untranslated regions*, tune how active the mRNA is.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] There are also many RNAs that are not translated, called non-coding RNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Like the untranslated regions, many of these non-coding RNAs have regulatory roles.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In nuclear polyadenylation, a poly(A) tail is added to an RNA at the end of transcription.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] On mRNAs, the poly(A) tail aids in transcription termination, export of the mRNA from the nucleus and translation by acting as a binding site of PABPC1.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Almost all eukaryotic mRNAs are polyadenylated, with the exception of animal replication-dependent histone mRNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] These are the only mRNAs in eukaryotes that lack a poly(A) tail, ending instead in a stem-loop structure followed by a purine-rich sequence, termed histone downstream element, that directs where the RNA is cut so that the 3′ end of the histone mRNA is formed.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Many eukaryotic non-coding RNAs are always polyadenylated at the end of transcription.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] There are small RNAs where the poly(A) tail is seen only in intermediary forms and not in the mature RNA as the ends are removed during processing, the notable ones being microRNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] But, for many long noncoding RNAs – a seemingly large group of regulatory RNAs that, for example, includes the RNA Xist, which mediates X chromosome inactivation – a poly(A) tail is part of the mature RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The processive polyadenylation complex in the nucleus of eukaryotes works on products of RNA polymerase II, such as precursor mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Here, a multi-protein complex *(see components on the right)* cleaves the 3′-most part of a newly produced RNA and polyadenylates the end produced by this cleavage.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The cleavage is catalysed by the enzyme CPSF and occurs 10–30 nucleotides downstream of its binding site.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This site often has the **polyadenylation signal** sequence AAUAAA on the RNA, but variants of it that bind more weakly to CPSF exist.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Two other proteins add specificity to the binding to an RNA: CstF and CFI.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] CstF binds to a GU-rich region further downstream of CPSF's site.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] CFI recognises a third site on the RNA (a set of UGUAA sequences in mammals) and can recruit CPSF even if the AAUAAA sequence is missing.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The polyadenylation signal – the sequence motif recognised by the RNA cleavage complex – varies between groups of eukaryotes.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Most human polyadenylation sites contain the AAUAAA sequence, but this sequence is less common in plants and fungi.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The RNA is typically cleaved before transcription termination, as CstF also binds to RNA polymerase II.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Through a poorly understood mechanism (as of 2002), it signals for RNA polymerase II to slip off of the transcript.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Cleavage also involves the protein CFII, though it is unknown how.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The cleavage site associated with a polyadenylation signal can vary up to some 50 nucleotides.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] When the RNA is cleaved, polyadenylation starts, catalysed by polyadenylate polymerase.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Polyadenylate polymerase builds the poly(A) tail by adding adenosine monophosphate units from adenosine triphosphate to the RNA, cleaving off pyrophosphate.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Another protein, PAB2, binds to the new, short poly(A) tail and increases the affinity of polyadenylate polymerase for the RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] When the poly(A) tail is approximately 250 nucleotides long the enzyme can no longer bind to CPSF and polyadenylation stops, thus determining the length of the poly(A) tail.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] CPSF is in contact with RNA polymerase II, allowing it to signal the polymerase to terminate transcription.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] When RNA polymerase II reaches a "termination sequence" (⁵'TTTATT3' on the DNA template and ⁵'AAUAAA3' on the primary transcript), the end of transcription is signaled.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The polyadenylation machinery is also physically linked to the spliceosome, a complex that removes introns from RNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The poly(A) tail acts as the binding site for poly(A)-binding protein.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Poly(A)-binding protein promotes export from the nucleus and translation, and inhibits degradation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This protein binds to the poly(A) tail prior to mRNA export from the nucleus and in yeast also recruits poly(A) nuclease, an enzyme that shortens the poly(A) tail and allows the export of the mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Poly(A)-binding protein is exported to the cytoplasm with the RNA. mRNAs that are not exported are degraded by the exosome.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Poly(A)-binding protein also can bind to, and thus recruit, several proteins that affect translation, one of these is initiation factor-4G, which in turn recruits the 40S ribosomal subunit.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] However, a poly(A) tail is not required for the translation of all mRNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Further, poly(A) tailing (oligo-adenylation) can determine the fate of RNA molecules that are usually not poly(A)-tailed (such as (small) non-coding (sn)RNAs etc.) and thereby induce their RNA decay.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In eukaryotic somatic cells, the poly(A) tails of most mRNAs in the cytoplasm gradually get shorter, and mRNAs with shorter poly(A) tail are translated less and degraded sooner.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] However, it can take many hours before an mRNA is degraded.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This deadenylation and degradation process can be accelerated by microRNAs complementary to the 3′ untranslated region of an mRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In immature egg cells, mRNAs with shortened poly(A) tails are not degraded, but are instead stored and translationally inactive.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] These short tailed mRNAs are activated by cytoplasmic polyadenylation after fertilisation, during egg activation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In animals, poly(A) ribonuclease (PARN) can bind to the 5′ cap and remove nucleotides from the poly(A) tail.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The level of access to the 5′ cap and poly(A) tail is important in controlling how soon the mRNA is degraded.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] PARN deadenylates less if the RNA is bound by the initiation factors 4E (at the 5′ cap) and 4G (at the poly(A) tail), which is why translation reduces deadenylation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The rate of deadenylation may also be regulated by RNA-binding proteins.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Additionally, RNA triple helix structures and RNA motifs such as the poly(A) tail 3' end binding pocket retard deadenylation process and inhibit poly(A) tail removal.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Once the poly(A) tail is removed, the decapping complex removes the 5′ cap, leading to a degradation of the RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Several other proteins are involved in deadenylation in budding yeast and human cells, most notably the CCR4-Not complex.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] There is polyadenylation in the cytosol of some animal cell types, namely in the germline, during early embryogenesis and in post-synaptic sites of nerve cells.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This lengthens the poly(A) tail of an mRNA with a shortened poly(A) tail, so that the mRNA will be translated.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] These shortened poly(A) tails are often less than 20 nucleotides, and are lengthened to around 80–150 nucleotides.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In the early mouse embryo, cytoplasmic polyadenylation of maternal RNAs from the egg cell allows the cell to survive and grow even though transcription does not start until the middle of the 2-cell stage (4-cell stage in human).
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In the brain, cytoplasmic polyadenylation is active during learning and could play a role in long-term potentiation, which is the strengthening of the signal transmission from a nerve cell to another in response to nerve impulses and is important for learning and memory formation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Cytoplasmic polyadenylation requires the RNA-binding proteins CPSF and CPEB, and can involve other RNA-binding proteins like Pumilio.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Depending on the cell type, the polymerase can be the same type of polyadenylate polymerase (PAP) that is used in the nuclear process, or the cytoplasmic polymerase GLD-2.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Many protein-coding genes have more than one polyadenylation site, so a gene can code for several mRNAs that differ in their 3′ end.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The 3' region of a transcript contains many polyadenylation signals (PAS).
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] When more proximal (closer towards 5' end) PAS sites are utilized, this shortens the length of the 3' untranslated region (3' UTR) of a transcript.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Studies in both humans and flies have shown tissue specific APA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] With neuronal tissues preferring distal PAS usage, leading to longer 3' UTRs and testis tissues preferring proximal PAS leading to shorter 3' UTRs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Studies have shown there is a correlation between a gene's conservation level and its tendency to do alternative polyadenylation, with highly conserved genes exhibiting more APA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Similarly, highly expressed genes follow this same pattern.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Ribo-sequencing data (sequencing of only mRNAs inside ribosomes) has shown that mRNA isoforms with shorter 3' UTRs are more likely to be translated.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Since alternative polyadenylation changes the length of the 3' UTR, it can also change which binding sites are available for microRNAs in the 3′ UTR.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] MicroRNAs tend to repress translation and promote degradation of the mRNAs they bind to, although there are examples of microRNAs that stabilise transcripts.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Alternative polyadenylation can also shorten the coding region, thus making the mRNA code for a different protein, but this is much less common than just shortening the 3′ untranslated region.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The choice of poly(A) site can be influenced by extracellular stimuli and depends on the expression of the proteins that take part in polyadenylation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] For example, the expression of CstF-64, a subunit of cleavage stimulatory factor (CstF), increases in macrophages in response to lipopolysaccharides (a group of bacterial compounds that trigger an immune response).
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This results in the selection of weak poly(A) sites and thus shorter transcripts.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This removes regulatory elements in the 3′ untranslated regions of mRNAs for defense-related products like lysozyme and TNF-α.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] These mRNAs then have longer half-lives and produce more of these proteins.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] RNA-binding proteins other than those in the polyadenylation machinery can also affect whether a polyadenylation site is used, as can DNA methylation near the polyadenylation signal.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In addition, numerous other components involved in transcription, splicing or other mechanisms regulating RNA biology can affect APA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] For many non-coding RNAs, including tRNA, rRNA, snRNA, and snoRNA, polyadenylation is a way of marking the RNA for degradation, at least in yeast.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This polyadenylation is done in the nucleus by the TRAMP complex, which maintains a tail that is around four nucleotides long on the 3′ end.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The RNA is then degraded by the exosome.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Poly(A) tails have also been found on human rRNA fragments, both the form of homopolymeric (A only) and heteropolymeric (mostly A) tails.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In many bacteria, both mRNAs and non-coding RNAs can be polyadenylated.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This poly(A) tail promotes degradation by the degradosome, which contains two RNA-degrading enzymes: **polynucleotide phosphorylase** and **RNase E**.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Polynucleotide phosphorylase binds to the 3′ end of RNAs and the 3′ extension provided by the poly(A) tail allows it to bind to the RNAs whose secondary structure would otherwise block the 3′ end.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Successive rounds of polyadenylation and degradation of the 3′ end by polynucleotide phosphorylase allows the **degradosome** to overcome these secondary structures.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The poly(A) tail can also recruit RNases that cut the RNA in two.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] These bacterial poly(A) tails are about 30 nucleotides long.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] In as different groups as animals and trypanosomes, the mitochondria contain both stabilising and destabilising poly(A) tails.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Destabilising polyadenylation targets both mRNA and noncoding RNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The poly(A) tails are 43 nucleotides long on average.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The stabilising ones start at the stop codon, and without them the stop codon (UAA) is not complete as the genome only encodes the U or UA part.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Plant mitochondria have only destabilising polyadenylation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Mitochondrial polyadenylation has never been observed in either budding or fission yeast.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] While many bacteria and mitochondria have polyadenylate polymerases, they also have another type of polyadenylation, performed by polynucleotide phosphorylase itself.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This enzyme is found in bacteria, mitochondria, plastids and as a constituent of the archaeal exosome (in those archaea that have an exosome).
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] It can synthesise a 3′ extension where the vast majority of the bases are adenines.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Like in bacteria, polyadenylation by polynucleotide phosphorylase promotes degradation of the RNA in plastids and likely also archaea.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Although polyadenylation is seen in almost all organisms, it is not universal.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] However, the wide distribution of this modification and the fact that it is present in organisms from all three domains of life implies that the last universal common ancestor of all living organisms, it is presumed, had some form of polyadenylation system.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] A few organisms do not polyadenylate mRNA, which implies that they have lost their polyadenylation machineries during evolution.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Although no examples of eukaryotes that lack polyadenylation are known, mRNAs from the bacterium *Mycoplasma gallisepticum* and the salt-tolerant archaean *Haloferax volcanii* lack this modification.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The most ancient polyadenylating enzyme is polynucleotide phosphorylase.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This enzyme is part of both the bacterial degradosome and the archaeal exosome, two closely related complexes that recycle RNA into nucleotides.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This enzyme degrades RNA by attacking the bond between the 3′-most nucleotides with a phosphate, breaking off a diphosphate nucleotide.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] This reaction is reversible, and so the enzyme can also extend RNA with more nucleotides.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The heteropolymeric tail added by polynucleotide phosphorylase is very rich in adenine.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The choice of adenine is most likely the result of higher ADP concentrations than other nucleotides as a result of using ATP as an energy currency, making it more likely to be incorporated in this tail in early lifeforms.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] It has been suggested that the involvement of adenine-rich tails in RNA degradation prompted the later evolution of polyadenylate polymerases (the enzymes that produce poly(A) tails with no other nucleotides in them).
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Polyadenylate polymerases are not as ancient.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] They have separately evolved in both bacteria and eukaryotes from CCA-adding enzyme, which is the enzyme that completes the 3′ ends of tRNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Its catalytic domain is homologous to that of other polymerases.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] It is presumed that the horizontal transfer of bacterial CCA-adding enzyme to eukaryotes allowed the archaeal-like CCA-adding enzyme to switch function to a poly(A) polymerase.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Some lineages, like archaea and cyanobacteria, never evolved a polyadenylate polymerase.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Polyadenylate tails are observed in several RNA viruses, including Influenza A, Coronavirus, Alfalfa mosaic virus, and Duck Hepatitis A.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Some viruses, such as HIV-1 and Poliovirus, inhibit the cell's poly-A binding protein (PABPC1) in order to emphasize their own genes' expression over the host cell's.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Poly(A)polymerase was first identified in 1960 as an enzymatic activity in extracts made from cell nuclei that could polymerise ATP, but not ADP, into polyadenine.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] Although identified in many types of cells, this activity had no known function until 1971, when poly(A) sequences were found in mRNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The only function of these sequences was thought at first to be protection of the 3′ end of the RNA from nucleases, but later the specific roles of polyadenylation in nuclear export and translation were identified.
[src:mrna-vaccines/polyadenylation] The polymerases responsible for polyadenylation were first purified and characterized in the 1960s and 1970s, but the large number of accessory proteins that control this process were discovered only in the early 1990s.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In molecular biology, **RNA polymerase** (abbreviated **RNAP** or **RNApol**), or more specifically **DNA-directed/dependent RNA polymerase** (**DdRP**), is an enzyme that catalyzes the chemical reactions that synthesize RNA from a DNA template strand.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Using the enzyme helicase, RNAP locally opens the double-stranded DNA so that one strand of the exposed nucleotides can be used as a template for the synthesis of RNA, a process called transcription.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] A transcription factor and its associated transcription mediator complex must be attached to a DNA binding site called a promoter region before RNAP can initiate the DNA unwinding at that position.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNAP not only initiates RNA transcription, it also guides the nucleotides into position, facilitates attachment and elongation, has intrinsic proofreading and replacement capabilities, and termination recognition capability.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Functions as an enzymatically active RNA molecule.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase is essential to life, and is found in all living organisms and many viruses.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Depending on the organism, a RNA polymerase can be a protein complex (multi-subunit RNAP) or only consist of one subunit (single-subunit RNAP, ssRNAP), each representing an independent lineage.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The former is found in bacteria, archaea, and eukaryotes alike, sharing a similar core structure and mechanism.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The latter is found in phages as well as eukaryotic chloroplasts and mitochondria, and is related to modern DNA polymerases.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Eukaryotic and archaeal RNAPs have more subunits than bacterial ones do, and are controlled differently.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Bacteria and archaea only have one RNA polymerase.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase II synthesizes precursors of mRNAs and most sRNA and microRNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase III synthesizes tRNAs, rRNA 5S and other small RNAs found in the nucleus and cytosol.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase IV and V found in plants are less understood; they make siRNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In addition to the ssRNAPs, chloroplasts also encode and use a bacteria-like RNAP.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In most prokaryotes, a single RNA polymerase species transcribes all types of RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase "core" from E. coli consists of five subunits: two alpha (α) subunits of 36 kDa, a beta (β) subunit of 150 kDa, a beta prime subunit (β′) of 155 kDa, and a small omega (ω) subunit.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] A sigma (σ) factor binds to the core, forming the holoenzyme.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] After transcription starts, the σ factor can unbind and let the core enzyme perform transcription.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The core RNA polymerase complex forms a "crab claw" or "clamp-jaw" structure with an internal channel running along the full length.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Eukaryotic and archaeal RNA polymerases have a similar core structure and work in a similar manner, although they have many extra subunits.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The 2006 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Roger D.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Kornberg for creating detailed molecular images of RNA polymerase during various stages of the transcription process.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] All RNAPs contain metal cofactors, in particular zinc and magnesium cations which aid in the transcription process.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Control of the process of gene transcription affects patterns of gene expression and, thereby, allows a cell to adapt to a changing environment, perform specialized roles within a multicellular organism, and maintain basic metabolic processes necessary for survival.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The activity of RNAP is complex and highly regulated.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In *Escherichia coli* bacteria, more than 100 transcription factors have been identified, which modify the activity of RNAP.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNAP can initiate transcription at specific DNA sequences known as promoters.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] It then produces an RNA chain, which is complementary to the template DNA strand.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The process of adding nucleotides to the RNA strand is known as elongation; in eukaryotes, RNAP can build chains as long as 2.4 million nucleotides (the full length of the dystrophin gene).
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNAP will preferentially release its RNA transcript at specific DNA sequences encoded at the end of genes, which are known as terminators.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] It is able to do this because specific interactions with the initiating nucleotide hold RNAP rigidly in place, facilitating chemical attack on the incoming nucleotide.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Such specific interactions explain why RNAP prefers to start transcripts with ATP (followed by GTP, UTP, and then CTP).
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In contrast to DNA polymerase, RNAP includes helicase activity, therefore no separate enzyme is needed to unwind DNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase binding in bacteria involves the sigma factor recognizing the core promoter region containing the −35 and −10 elements (located *before* the beginning of sequence to be transcribed) and also, at some promoters, the α subunit C-terminal domain recognizing promoter upstream elements.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] There are multiple interchangeable sigma factors, each of which recognizes a distinct set of promoters.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] For example, in *E. coli*, σ70 is expressed under normal conditions and recognizes promoters for genes required under normal conditions ("housekeeping genes"), while σ32 recognizes promoters for genes required at high temperatures ("heat-shock genes").
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In archaea and eukaryotes, the functions of the bacterial general transcription factor sigma are performed by multiple general transcription factors that work together.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] After binding to the DNA, the RNA polymerase switches from a closed complex to an open complex.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] This change involves the separation of the DNA strands to form an unwound section of DNA of approximately 13 bp, referred to as the "transcription bubble".
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Supercoiling plays an important part in polymerase activity because of the unwinding and rewinding of DNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Because regions of DNA in front of RNAP are unwound, there are compensatory positive supercoils.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Regions behind RNAP are rewound and negative supercoils are present.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase then starts to synthesize the initial DNA-RNA heteroduplex, with ribonucleotides base-paired to the template DNA strand according to Watson-Crick base-pairing interactions.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] As noted above, RNA polymerase makes contacts with the promoter region.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] However these stabilizing contacts inhibit the enzyme's ability to access DNA further downstream and thus the synthesis of the full-length product.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In order to continue RNA synthesis, RNA polymerase must escape the promoter.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] It must maintain promoter contacts while unwinding more downstream DNA for synthesis, "scrunching" more downstream DNA into the initiation complex.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] During the promoter escape transition, RNA polymerase is considered a "stressed intermediate." Thermodynamically the stress accumulates from the DNA-unwinding and DNA-compaction activities.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Once the DNA-RNA heteroduplex is long enough (~10 bp), RNA polymerase releases its upstream contacts and effectively achieves the promoter escape transition into the elongation phase.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The heteroduplex at the active center stabilizes the elongation complex.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] However, promoter escape is not the only outcome.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase can also relieve the stress by releasing its downstream contacts, arresting transcription.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The paused transcribing complex has two options: (1) release the nascent transcript and begin anew at the promoter or (2) re-establish a new 3′-OH on the nascent transcript at the active site via RNA polymerase's catalytic activity and recommence DNA scrunching to achieve promoter escape.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Abortive initiation, the unproductive cycling of RNA polymerase before the promoter escape transition, results in short RNA fragments of around 9 bp in a process known as abortive transcription.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The extent of abortive initiation depends on the presence of transcription factors and the strength of the promoter contacts.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The 17-bp transcriptional complex has an 8-bp DNA-RNA hybrid, that is, 8 base-pairs involve the RNA transcript bound to the DNA template strand.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] As transcription progresses, ribonucleotides are added to the 3′ end of the RNA transcript and the RNAP complex moves along the DNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The characteristic elongation rates in prokaryotes and eukaryotes are about 10–100 nts/sec.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Aspartyl (asp) residues in the RNAP will hold on to Mg2+ ions, which will, in turn, coordinate the phosphates of the ribonucleotides.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The first Mg2+ will hold on to the α-phosphate of the NTP to be added.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] This allows the nucleophilic attack of the 3′-OH from the RNA transcript, adding another NTP to the chain.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The second Mg2+ will hold on to the pyrophosphate of the NTP.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Unlike the proofreading mechanisms of DNA polymerase those of RNAP have only recently been investigated.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Proofreading begins with separation of the mis-incorporated nucleotide from the DNA template.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The polymerase then backtracks by one position and cleaves the dinucleotide that contains the mismatched nucleotide.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In the RNA polymerase this occurs at the same active site used for polymerization and is therefore markedly different from the DNA polymerase where proofreading occurs at a distinct nuclease active site.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The overall error rate is around 10−4 to 10−6.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In bacteria, termination of RNA transcription can be rho-dependent or rho-independent.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The former relies on the rho factor, which destabilizes the DNA-RNA heteroduplex and causes RNA release.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The latter, also known as intrinsic termination, relies on a palindromic region of DNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Transcribing the region causes the formation of a "hairpin" structure from the RNA transcription looping and binding upon itself.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] This hairpin structure is often rich in G-C base-pairs, making it more stable than the DNA-RNA hybrid itself.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] As a result, the 8 bp DNA-RNA hybrid in the transcription complex shifts to a 4 bp hybrid.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] These last 4 base pairs are weak A-U base pairs, and the entire RNA transcript will fall off the DNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Transcription termination in eukaryotes is less well understood than in bacteria, but involves cleavage of the new transcript followed by template-independent addition of adenines at its new 3′ end, in a process called polyadenylation.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Given that DNA and RNA polymerases both carry out template-dependent nucleotide polymerization, it might be expected that the two types of enzymes would be structurally related.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] One lineage led to the modern DNA polymerases and reverse transcriptases, as well as to a few single-subunit RNA polymerases (ssRNAP) from phages and organelles.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The other multi-subunit RNAP lineage formed all of the modern cellular RNA polymerases.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In bacteria, the same enzyme catalyzes the synthesis of mRNA and non-coding RNA (ncRNA).
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The β′ subunit is the largest subunit, and is encoded by the rpoC gene.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The β′ subunit contains part of the active center responsible for RNA synthesis and contains some of the determinants for non-sequence-specific interactions with DNA and nascent RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] It is split into two subunits in Cyanobacteria and chloroplasts.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The β subunit contains the rest of the active center responsible for RNA synthesis and contains the rest of the determinants for non-sequence-specific interactions with DNA and nascent RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The ω subunit facilitates assembly of RNAP and stabilizes assembled RNAP.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In order to bind promoters, RNAP core associates with the transcription initiation factor sigma (σ) to form RNA polymerase holoenzyme.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Sigma reduces the affinity of RNAP for nonspecific DNA while increasing specificity for promoters, allowing transcription to initiate at correct sites.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The complete holoenzyme therefore has 6 subunits: β′βαI and αIIωσ (~450 kDa).
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Eukaryotes have multiple types of nuclear RNAP, each responsible for synthesis of a distinct subset of RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase II synthesizes precursors of mRNAs and most snRNA and microRNAs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] This is the most studied type, and, due to the high level of control required over transcription, a range of transcription factors are required for its binding to promoters.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase IV synthesizes siRNA in plants.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNA polymerase V synthesizes RNAs involved in siRNA-directed heterochromatin formation in plants.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Eukaryotic chloroplasts contain a multi-subunit RNAP ("PEP, plastid-encoded polymerase").
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Due to its bacterial origin, the organization of PEP resembles that of current bacterial RNA polymerases: It is encoded by the RPOA, RPOB, RPOC1 and RPOC2 genes on the plastome, which as proteins form the core subunits of PEP, respectively named α, β, β′ and β″.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Similar to the RNA polymerase in *E. coli*, PEP requires the presence of sigma (σ) factors for the recognition of its promoters, containing the -10 and -35 motifs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Initially, a group consisting of 10 PAPs was identified through biochemical methods, which was later extended to 12 PAPs.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Chloroplast also contain a second, structurally and mechanistically unrelated, single-subunit RNAP ("nucleus-encoded polymerase, NEP").
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Eukaryotic mitochondria use POLRMT (human), a nucleus-encoded single-subunit RNAP.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Such phage-like polymerases are referred to as RpoT in plants.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Archaea have a single type of RNAP, responsible for the synthesis of all RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Archaeal RNAP is structurally and mechanistically similar to bacterial RNAP and eukaryotic nuclear RNAP I-V, and is especially closely structurally and mechanistically related to eukaryotic nuclear RNAP II.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The history of the discovery of the archaeal RNA polymerase is quite recent.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] The first analysis of the RNAP of an archaeon was performed in 1971, when the RNAP from the extreme halophile *Halobacterium cutirubrum* was isolated and purified.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Crystal structures of RNAPs from *Sulfolobus solfataricus* and *Sulfolobus shibatae* set the total number of identified archaeal subunits at thirteen.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Archaea has the subunit corresponding to Eukaryotic Rpb1 split into two.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] There is no homolog to eukaryotic Rpb9 (POLR2I) in the *S. shibatae* complex, although TFS (TFIIS homolog) has been proposed as one based on similarity.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] There is an additional subunit dubbed Rpo13; together with Rpo5 it occupies a space filled by an insertion found in bacterial β′ subunits (1,377–1,420 in *Taq*).
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] An earlier, lower-resolution study on *S. solfataricus* structure did not find Rpo13 and only assigned the space to Rpo5/Rpb5.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Rpo3 is notable in that it's an iron–sulfur protein.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNAP I/III subunit AC40 found in some eukaryotes share similar sequences, but does not bind iron.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] This domain, in either case, serves a structural function.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Archaeal RNAP subunit previously used an "RpoX" nomenclature where each subunit is assigned a letter in a way unrelated to any other systems.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] In 2009, a new nomenclature based on Eukaryotic Pol II subunit "Rpb" numbering was proposed.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Orthopoxviruses and some other nucleocytoplasmic large DNA viruses synthesize RNA using a virally encoded multi-subunit RNAP.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] They are most similar to eukaryotic RNAPs, with some subunits minified or removed.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Exactly which RNAP they are most similar to is a topic of debate.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Most other viruses that synthesize RNA use unrelated mechanics.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Many viruses use a single-subunit DNA-dependent RNAP (ssRNAP) that is structurally and mechanistically related to the single-subunit RNAP of eukaryotic chloroplasts (RpoT) and mitochondria (POLRMT) and, more distantly, to DNA polymerases and reverse transcriptases.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Perhaps the most widely studied such single-subunit RNAP is bacteriophage T7 RNA polymerase. ssRNAPs cannot proofread.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] B. subtilis prophage SPβ uses YonO, a homolog of the β+β′ subunits of msRNAPs to form a monomeric (both barrels on the same chain) RNAP distinct from the usual "right hand" ssRNAP.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] It probably diverged very long ago from the canonical five-unit msRNAP, before the time of the last universal common ancestor.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] Other viruses use an RNA-dependent RNAP (an RNAP that employs RNA as a template instead of DNA).
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] This occurs in negative strand RNA viruses and dsRNA viruses, both of which exist for a portion of their life cycle as double-stranded RNA.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] However, some positive strand RNA viruses, such as poliovirus, also contain RNA-dependent RNAP.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] RNAP was discovered independently by Sam Weiss, Audrey Stevens, and Jerard Hurwitz in 1960.
[src:mrna-vaccines/rna-polymerase] By this time, one half of the 1959 Nobel Prize in Medicine had been awarded to Severo Ochoa for the discovery of what was believed to be RNAP, but instead turned out to be polynucleotide phosphorylase.
